  });
  console.log('After copyAsync');

  console.log('Database copied successfully!');
} catch (error) {
  console.error('An error occurred while copying the database:', error);
}
```

### 2. Check the Asset URI

The URI in your logs shows that the asset is being fetched from a local server (`http://192.168.0.101:19000`). Ensure that this server is running and accessible from your device/emulator. You can try to access this URL directly in a web browser to see if the database file is available.

### 3. Check the Asset Type

Make sure that the asset type is correctly set up in your project. If you're using Expo, ensure that the database file is included in your project and correctly referenced in your `app.json` or `app.config.js` under the `assetBundlePatterns` section.

Example:
```json
{
  "expo": {
    "assetBundlePatterns": [
      "**/*"
    ]
  }
}
```

### 4. Permissions

If you're running on a physical device, ensure that your app has the necessary permissions to read and write files. You can check and request permissions using the `expo-permissions` library:

```javascript
import * as Permissions from 'expo-permissions';

const { status } = await Permissions.askAsync(Permissions.MEDIA_LIBRARY);
if (status !== 'granted') {
  console.error('Permission not granted');
  return;
}
