 To close one Electron window and give focus to another window in Electron, you can use the `electron` module's `webContents` property and the `close` method.
Here's an example:
```
const electron = require('electron');

let mainWindow = new electron.Window({
  width: 800,
  height: 600,
  webContents: new electron.WebContents({
    // This will close the main window when the user clicks on the cross
    close: function() {
      mainWindow.close();
    }
  })
});
```
In the above code, we create a new `electron.Window` with a width and height of 800x600 pixels, and we set the `webContents` property to a new `electron.WebContents` instance. We then define a `close` function that will be called when the user clicks on the cross in the window. When the `close` function is called, it will close the `mainWindow` using the `close` method.
You can also use `electron.Menu` to create a menu item that will close the window when clicked.
```
const electron = require('electron');
let mainWindow = new electron.Window({
  width: 800,
  height: 600,
  webContents: new electron.WebContents({
    // This will close the main window when the user clicks on the menu item
    menu: [
      {
        label: 'Close',
        accelerator: 'Ctrl+W',
        click: function() {
          mainWindow.close();
        }
      }
    ]
  })
});
```
In the above code, we create a `electron.Menu` instance and add a menu item with the label "Close". When the user clicks on the menu item, the `click` function will be called, which will close the `mainWindow` using the `close` method.
You can also use `electron.Menu` to create a menu item that will close the window when the user presses the `Ctrl+W` keyboard shortcut.
You can also use `electron.ipcMain` to communicate between windows, and close the window from another window using `electron.ipcMain.send` method.
It's important to note that closing a window will close all the tabs and windows inside that window, so be careful when using this method.

