x = [1 1.1 1.2 1.3 1.4 1.5 1.6 1.7 1.8 1.9 2];
y = [714 741 804 814 833 865 872 878 900 898 887];
w = [4719 4310 4002 3769 3592 3458 3359 3288 3241 3215 3207];

% Transform the data
ln_y = log(y);

% Apply weighted linear least squares
X = [ones(size(x)); x]';
W = diag(w);
A = (X' * W * X) \ (X' * W * ln_y); % A(1) = b0, A(2) = m

% Calculate standard deviations of b0 and m
y_fit = X * A;
residuals = ln_y - y_fit;
s_squared = (residuals' * W * residuals) / (length(x) - 2);
SD = sqrt(s_squared * diag(inv(X' * W * X))); % standard deviations of b0 and m

b. Solve for the original unknown parameters a and m, and their standard deviations:

a = exp(A(1));
m = A(2);
a_SD = a * SD(1); % Standard deviation of a
m_SD = SD(2); % Standard deviation of m

c. Plot the original data and the fitted curve on the same figure:

xx = linspace(min(x),max(x),100);
yy = a * xx .* exp(m * xx);
figure;
plot(x, y, 'bo', 'MarkerSize', 10); % Original data
hold on;
plot(xx, yy,'r'); % Fitted curve
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');
legend('Original data', 'Fitted curve');
title('Original data and fitted curve');

d. Estimate the adjusted observations y_hat and their standard deviations:

y_hat = a * x .* exp(m * x);
y_hat_SD = sqrt(s_squared * diag((X * inv(X' * W * X)) * X)); % Standard deviations of y_hat

e. Add the adjusted observations y_hat to the figure:

errorbar(x, y_hat, y_hat_SD, 'g*');
hold off;
legend('Original data', 'Fitted curve', 'Adjusted observations');
title('Original data and fitted curve');

Which part of the curve can be better trusted:

The middle part of the curve can be better trusted, as the standard deviations of the adjusted observations are smaller there which means the fitted curve is more certain in that region.
